e.', 1779, 0), (404897, 'No man is good enough to govern another man without that other''s consent.', 1012, 0), (404898, 'One can present people with opportunities. One cannot make them equal to them.', 33993, 0), (404899, 'Parliament is the longest running farce in the West End.', 64073, 0), (404900, 'States  like men  have their growth  their manhood  their decrepitude  their decay.', 8764, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (404901, 'The enemies of Freedom do not argue  they shout and they shoot.', 62527, 0), (404902, 'The entire civil service is like a fortress  made of papers  forms and red tape.', 64074, 0), (404903, 'The king reigns  but does not govern.', 64075, 0), (404904, 'The point to remember is that what the Government gives it must first take away.', 64076, 0), (404905, 'There''s no place for the state in the bedrooms of the nation.', 62745, 0), (404906, 'Tyranny is always better organized than freedom.', 9561, 0), (404907, 'We have a tried and tested system of government that  in being so flexible  exists as a great ghost that no one has dared to conjure into flesh.', 64077, 0), (404908, 'When the freedom they wished for most was the freedom from responsibility  then Athens ceased to be free and never was free again.', 749, 0), (404909, 'Wherever you have an efficient government you have a dictatorship.', 16121, 0), (404910, 'While the people retain their virtue and vigilence  no administration  by any extreme of wickedness or folly  can very seriously injure the government in the short space of four years.', 1012, 0), (404911, 'Any people anywhere  being inclined and having the power  have the right to rise up and shake off the existing government and form a new one. This is a most valuable and sacred right - a right which we hope and believe is to liberate the world.', 1012, 0), (404912, 'No man should be in public office who can''t make more money in private life.', 62499, 0), (404913, 'Government is the only institution that can take a valuable commodity like paper  and make it worthless by applying ink.', 64078, 0), (404914, 'The poorest man may in his cottage bid defiance to all the force of the crown. It may be frail - its roof may shake - the wind may blow through it - the storm may enter - the rain may enter - but the King of England cannot enter! - all his force dares not cross the threshhold of the ruined tenement!', 64079, 0), (404915, 'The art of government is the organization of idolatry.', 266, 0), (404916, 'Every government is run by liars and nothing they say should be believed.', 17525, 0), (404917, 'The more the world is specialized the more it will be run by generalists.', 64080, 0), (404918, 'We are under a Constitution  but the Constitution is what the judges say it is.', 63019, 0), (404919, 'A friend of mine says that every man who takes office in Washington either grows or swells  and when I give a man an office  I watch him carefully to see whether he is swelling or growing.', 1970, 0), (404920, 'The majority is the best way  because it is visible  and has strength to make itself obeyed. Yet it is the opinion of the least able.', 144, 0), (404921, 'The best government is a benevolent tyranny tempered by an occasional assassination.', 808, 0), (404922, 'No man ever saw a government. I live in the midst of the Government of the United States  but I never saw the Government of the United States.', 1970, 0), (404923, 'The State  that cawing rookery of committees and subcommittees.', 9765, 0), (404924, 'The weak have one weapon - the errors of those who think they are strong.', 64081, 0), (404925, 'Government in the last analysis is organised opinion. Where there is little or no public opinion  there is likely to be bad government  which sooner or later becomes autocratic government.', 62778, 0), (404926, 'Under democracy  one party always devotes its chief energies to trying to prove that the other party is unfit to rule - and both commonly succeed  and are right.', 411, 0), (404927, 'Inflation is one form of taxation that can be imposed without legislation.', 16707, 0), (404928, 'Doing what''s right isn''t the problem. It''s knowing what''s right.', 1763, 0), (404929, 'It is the aim of good government to stimulate production  of bad government to encourage consumption.', 64082, 0), (404930, 'Bureaucracy  the rule of no one  has become the modern form of despotism.', 8417, 0), (404931, 'Be thankful we''re not getting all the government we''re paying for.', 1122, 0), (404932, 'A government that is big enough to give you all you want is big enough to take it all away.', 64083, 0), (404933, 'Government is the political representative of a natural equilibrium  of custom  of inertia  it is by no means a representative of reason.', 2683, 0), (404934, 'The best reason why monarchy is a strong government is that it is an intelligible government: the mass of mankind understand it  and they hardly anywhere in the world understand any other.', 1432, 0), (404935, 'The world is ruled only by consideration of advantages.', 62336, 0), (404936, 'Must a government of necessity be too strong for the liberties of its people or too weak to maintain its own existence?', 1012, 0), (404937, 'As I get older ... I become more convinced that good government is not a substitute for self-government.', 64084, 0), (404938, 'Every man wishes to pursue his occupation and to enjoy the fruits of his labours and the produce of his property in peace and safety  and with the least possible expense. When these things are accomplished  all the objects for which government ought to be established are answered.', 1207, 0), (404939, 'A monarchy is a merchantman  which sails well  but will sometimes strike on a rock and go to the bottom  whilst a republic is a raft which will never sink  but then your feet are always in water.', 64085, 0), (404940, 'The state  it cannot too often be repeated  does nothing  and can give nothing  which it does not take from somebody.', 40782, 0), (404941, 'Government  even in its best state  is but a necessary evil  in its worst state  an intolerable one.', 1131, 0), (404942, 'Government is not reason  it is not eloquence - it is force.', 3161, 0), (404943, 'Bureaucracy is a giant mechanism operated by pygmies.', 143, 0), (404944, 'Whenever by an unfortunate occurrence of circumstances an opposition is compelled to support the 