ession of as much happiness as is good for any of the children of Adam.', 17007, 0), (405341, 'The greatest happiness you can have is knowing that you do not necessarily require happiness.', 2919, 0), (405342, 'Existence is a strange bargain. Life owes us little  we owe it everything. The only true happiness comes from squandering ourselves for a purpose.', 8676, 0), (405343, 'Even if we can''t be happy  we must always be cheerful.', 64114, 0), (405344, 'New Year''s Day is every man''s birthday.', 2182, 0), (405345, 'Happiness is the perpetual possession of being well deceived.', 9058, 0), (405346, 'To be without some of the things you want is an indispensable part of happiness.', 95, 0), (405347, 'For the rational  psychologically healthy man  the desire for pleasure is the desire to celebrate his control over reality. For the neurotic  the desire for pleasure is the desire to escape from reality.', 6169, 0), (405348, 'It has never been given to a man to attain at once his happiness and his salvation.', 9561, 0), (405349, 'If thou workest at that which is before thee  following right reason seriously  vigorously  calmly  without allowing anything else to distract thee  but keeping thy divine part pure  as if thou shouldst be bound to give it back immediately  if thou holdest to this  expecting nothing  fearing nothing  but satisfied with thy present activity according to Nature  and with heroic truth in every word and sound which thou utterest  thou wilt live happy. And there is no man who is able to prevent this.', 267, 0), (405350, 'We act as though comfort and luxury were the chief requirements of life  when all that we need to make us really happy is something to be enthusiastic about.', 3036, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (405351, 'One thing I know: the only ones among you who will be really happy are those who will have sought and found how to serve.', 1006, 0), (405352, 'Happiness is the light on the water. The water is cold and dark and deep.', 15654, 0), (405353, 'Happiness: a good bank account  a good cook and a good digestion.', 1372, 0), (405354, 'Knowledge of what is possible is the beginning of happiness.', 2683, 0), (405355, 'Happiness is the interval between periods of unhappiness.', 2692, 0), (405356, 'Weeping may endure for a night  but joy cometh in the morning.', 5587, 0), (405357, 'Behold  we count them happy which endure. Ye have heard of the patience of Job.', 5587, 0), (405358, 'The will of man is his happiness.', 62336, 0), (405359, 'Man''s happiness springs mainly from moderate troubles  which afford the mind a healthful stimulus  and are followed by a reaction which produces a cheerful flow of spirits.', 64115, 0), (405360, 'There is only one way to happiness and that is to cease worrying about things which are beyond the power of our will.', 1328, 0), (405361, 'It is nonsense to speak of ''higher'' and ''lower'' pleasures. To a hungry man it is  rightly  more important that he eat than that he philosophize.', 219, 0), (405362, 'The secret of happiness is not in doing what one likes  but in liking what one has to do.', 64116, 0), (405363, 'True happiness is of a retired nature and an enemy to pomp and noise  it arises  in the first place  from the enjoyment of one''s self  and  in the next  from the friendship and conversations of a few select companions.', 2868, 0), (405364, 'I have known some quite good people who were unhappy  but never an interested person who was unhappy.', 11232, 0), (405365, 'My creed is that: Happiness is the only good. The place to be happy is here. The time to be happy is now. The way to be happy is to make others so.', 1980, 0), (405366, 'My life has no purpose  no direction  no aim  no meaning  and yet I''m happy. I can''t figure it out. What am I doing right?', 151, 0), (405367, 'Happiness to a dog is what lies on the other side of a door.', 62223, 0), (405368, 'Happiness comes fleetingly now and then  To those who have learned to do without it And to them only.', 2692, 0), (405369, 'I believe in the possibility of happiness  if one cultivates intuition and outlives the grosser passions  including optimism.', 2683, 0), (405370, 'Happiness is brief It will not stay. God batters at its sails.', 542, 0), (405371, 'To be happy  we must not be too concerned with others.', 532, 0), (405372, '. . . the little hills rejoice on every side. The pastures are clothed with flocks  the valleys also are covered over with corn  they shout for joy  they also sing.', 5587, 0), (405373, 'For each ecstatic instant We must an anguish pay In keen and quivering ratio To the ecstasy.', 91, 0), (405374, 'At rare moments in history  by a series of accidents never to be repeated  arise flower societies in which the cult of happiness is paramount  hedonistic  mindless  intent upon the glorious physical instant.', 64117, 0), (405375, 'Man is that he might have joy.', 3554, 0), (405376, 'The formula for complete happiness is to be very busy with the unimportant.', 6168, 0), (405377, 'Make happy those who are near  and those who are far will come.', 7652, 0), (405378, 'Remember that happiness is a way of travel - not a destination.', 64118, 0), (405379, 'If we cannot live so as to be happy  let us at least live so as to deserve it.', 64119, 0), (405380, 'I never admired another''s fortune so much that I became dissatisfied with my own.', 20928, 0), (405381, 'Happiness is essentially a state of going somewhere  wholeheartedly  one-directionally  without regret or reservation.', 64019, 0), (405382, 'Happiness? That''s nothing more than health and a poor memory.', 1006, 0), (405383, 'Happiness is the only sanction of life  where happiness fails  existence remains a mad and lamentable experiment.', 2683, 0), (405384, 'Happiness makes up in height for what it lacks in length.', 35, 0), (405385, 'It is not easy to find happiness in ourselves  and it is not possible to find it elsewhere.', 24996, 0), (405386, 'Happiness depends  as Nature shows  Less on exterior things than most suppose.', 8676, 0), (405387, 'Happiness is a small and unworthy goal for something as big and fancy as a whole lifetime  and should be taken in small doses.', 9597, 0), (405388, 'To be without some of the things you want is an indispensable part of happiness.', 95, 0), (405389, 'Man is fond of counting his troubles  but he does not count his joys. If he counted them up as he ought to  he would see that every lot has enough happiness provided for it.', 57, 0), (405390, 'Happiness is itself a kind of gratitude.', 38001, 0), (405391, 'I am happy and content because I think I am.', 64120, 0), (405392, 'Unhappy is the man  though he rule the world  who doesn''t consider himself supremely blessed.', 62237, 0), (405393, 'The happiness which is lacking makes one think even the happiness one has unbearable.', 563, 0), (405394, 'Happiness is a result of the relative strengths of positive and negative feelings  rather than an absolute amount of one or the other.', 64121, 0), (405395, 'The best way for a person to have happy thoughts is to count his blessings and not his cash.', 33, 0), (405396, 'Surfeits of happiness are fatal.', 1255, 0), (405397, 'If thou wouldst be happy ... have an indifference for more than what is sufficient.', 3256, 0), (405398, 'You will live wisely if you are happy in your lot.', 2542, 0), (405399, 'We always have enough to be happy if we are enjoying what we do have- and not worrying about what we don''t have.', 62252, 0), (405400, 'Talk happiness. The world is sad enough without your woe. No path is wholly rough.', 541, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (405401, 'When a man has lost all happiness  he''s not alive. Call him a breathing corpse.', 139, 0), (405402, 'Whether you are talking about education  career  or service  you are talking about life. And life must really have joy. It''s supposed to be fun.', 11962, 0), (405403, 'Why is it that people who cannot show feeling presume that that is a strength and not a weakness?', 996, 0), (405404, 'Happiness is the meaning and the purpose of life  the whole aim and end of human existence', 1116, 0), (405405, 'Happiness is the only sanction in life  where happiness fails  existence remains a mad and lamentable experiment.', 2683, 0), (405406, 'The pursuit of happiness ... is the greatest feat man has to accomplish.', 19737, 0), (405407, 'Make us happy and you make us good.', 698, 0), (405408, 'A good laugh makes any interview  or any conversation  so much better.', 64122, 0), (405409, 'The joyfulness of a man prolongeth his days.', 5587, 0), (405410, 'I love myself when I am laughing.', 751, 0), (405411, 'Everyone  without exception  is searching for happiness.', 144, 0), (405412, 'I will not be just a tourist in the world of images  just watching images passing by which I cannot live in  make love to  possess as permanent sources of joy and ecstasy.', 23, 0), (405413, 'Celebrate the happiness that friends are always giving  make every day a holiday and celebrate just living!', 64123, 0), (405414, 'Live all you can  it''s a mistake not to. It doesn''t so much matter what you do in particular  so long as you have your life. If you haven''t had that  what have you had?', 561, 0), (405415, 'Is life worth living? Aye  with the best of us  Heights of us  depths of us- Life is the test of us!', 63856, 0), (405416, 'The general rule is that people who enjoy life also enjoy marriage.', 64124, 0), (405417, 'It is only by expressing all that is inside that purer and purer streams come.', 1516, 0), (405418, 'Age does not protect you from love but love to some extent protects you from age.', 52500, 0), (405419, 'There is no cure for birth and death save to enjoy the interval.', 2683, 0), (405420, 'I don''t want to get to the end of my life and find that I lived just the length of it. I want to have lived the width of it as well.', 8213, 0), (405421, 'Men are made for happiness  and anyone who is completely happy has a right to say to himself: "I am doing God''s will on earth."', 1390, 0), (405422, 'To live is so startling it leaves little time for anything else.', 91, 0), (405423, 'Living well and beautifully and justly are all one thing.', 1595, 0), (405424, 'Without pleasure man would live like a fool and soon die.', 64125, 0), (405425, 'Life has got to be lived-that''s all that there is to it.', 141, 0), (405426, 'All animals except man know that the principle business of life is to enjoy it.', 4111, 0), (405427, 'Everything holds its breath except spring. She bursts through as strong as ever.', 11972, 0), (405428, 'To live as fully  as completely as possible  to be happy ... is the true aim and end to life.', 64126, 0), (405429, 'This is life! It can harden and it can exalt!', 845, 0), (405430, 'All I can say about life is  Oh God  enjoy it!', 51805, 0), (405431, 'It is in his pleasure that a man really lives.', 24996, 0), (405432, 'Happiness hates the timid!', 6194, 0), (405433, 'I have smelt all the aromas there are in the fragrant kitchen they call Earth  and what we can enjoy in this life  I surely have enjoyed just like a lord!', 1158, 0), (405434, 'Man is that he might have joy.', 3554, 0), (405435, 'It is better to be happy for a moment and be burned up with beauty than to live a long time and be bored all the while.', 2692, 0), (405436, 'If you want to die happily  learn to live  if you would live happily  learn to die.', 64127, 0), (405437, 'Happiness comes more from loving than being loved  and often when our affection seems wounded it is only our vanity bleeding. To love  and to be hurt often  and to love again-this is the brave and happy life.', 64128, 0), (405438, 'The true object of all human life is play.', 263, 0), (405439, 'The right to happiness is fundamental.', 5934, 0), (405440, 'Love lights more fires than hate extinguishes  And men grow better as the world grows old.', 541, 0), (405441, 'The Eskimos had fifty-two names for snow because it was important to them  there ought to be as many for love.', 114, 0), (405442, 'Not all of us have to possess earth-shaking talent. Just common sense and love will do.', 64129, 0), (405443, 'The secret of a happy marriage is finding the right person. You know they''re right if you love to be with them all of the time.', 1537, 0), (405444, 'We can sometimes love what we do not understand  but it is impossible completely to understand what we do not love.', 63997, 0), (405445, 'To serve thy generation  this thy fate: "Written in water " swiftly fades thy name  But he who loves his kind does  first or late  A work too great for fame.', 64130, 0), (405446, 'Love and respect are the most important aspects of parenting  and of all relationships.', 63992, 0), (405447, 'Perhaps the best function of parenthood is to teach the young creature to love with safety  so that it may be able to venture unafraid when later emotion comes  the thwarting of the instinct to love is the root of all sorrow and not sex only but divinity itself is insulted when it is repressed. To disapprove  to condemn-the human soul shrivels under barren righteousness.', 21457, 0), (405448, 'Love  I find  is like singing. Everybody can do enough to satisfy themselves  though it may not impress the neighbors as being very much.', 751, 0), (405449, 'Love is the same as like except you feel sexier.', 29209, 0), (405450, 'Love is the only thing we can carry with us when we go  and it makes the end so easy.', 296, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (405451, 'Love  by its very nature  is unworldly  and it is for this reason rather than its rarity that it is not only apolitical but anti-political  perhaps the most powerful of all anti-political human forces.', 2694, 0), (405452, 'I love  and the world is mine!', 63703, 0), (405453, 'When love is out of your life  you''re through in a way. Because while it is there it''s like a motor that''s going  you have such vitality to do things  big things  because love is goosing you all the time.', 18086, 0), (405454, 'A caress is better than a career.', 63830, 0), (405455, 'I don''t want to live-I want to love first  and live incidentally.', 45, 0), (405456, 'What is it that love does to a woman? Without it  she only sleeps  with it alone  she lives.', 4093, 0), (405457, 'What a richly colored strong warm coat is woven when love is the warp and work is the woof.', 8930, 0), (405458, 'We cannot really love anybody with whom we never laugh.', 24996, 0), (405459, 'There is only one happiness in life  to love and be loved.', 810, 0), (405460, 'When you come right down to it  the secret of having it all is loving it all.', 62254, 0), (405461, 'Where there is great love  there are always wishes.', 307, 0), (405462, 'The cure for all ills and wrongs  the cares  the sorrows and the crimes of humanity  all lie in the one word ''love.'' It is the divine vitality that everywhere produces and restores life.', 59119, 0), (405463, 'To love is to receive a glimpse of heaven.', 64131, 0), (405464, 'Love is a force more formidable than any other. It is invisible-it cannot be seen or measured  yet it is powerful enough to transform you in a moment  and offer you more joy than any material possession could.', 28913, 0), (405465, 'Love is the only effective counter to death.', 62362, 0), (405466, 'There are only two things that are absolute realities  love and knowledge  and you can''t escape them.', 25143, 0), (405467, 'There is nothing ridiculous in love.', 25143, 0), (405468, 'Our society allows people to be absolutely neurotic and totally out of touch with their feelings and everyone else''s feelings  and yet be very respectable.', 8628, 0), (405469, 'From the moment we walk out the door until we come back home our sensibilities are so assaulted by the world that we have to soak up as much love as we can get  simply to arm ourselves.', 57186, 0), (405470, 'Infatuation is when you think that he''s as sexy as Robert Redford  as smart as Henry Kissinger  as noble as Ralph Nader  as funny as Woody Allen  and as athletic as Jimmy Conners. Love is when you realize that he''s as sexy as Woody Allen  as smart as Jimmy Conners  as funny as Ralph Nader  as athletic as Henry Kissinger  and nothing like Robert Redford-but you''ll take him anyway.', 29209, 0), (405471, 'I was in love with the whole world and all that lived in its rainy arms.', 43, 0), (405472, '''Tis what I love determines how I love.', 215, 0), (405473, 'Not only is there a right to be happy  there is a duty to be happy. So much sadness exists in the world that we are all under obligation to contribute as much joy as lies within our powers.', 64132, 0), (405474, 'There is no duty so much underrated as the duty of being happy.', 449, 0), (405475, 'Pleasure is the object  duty and the goal of all rational creatures.', 808, 0), (405476, 'Different men seek ... happiness in different ways and by different means.', 1116, 0), (405477, 'What''s joy to one is a nightmare to the other.', 1140, 0), (405478, 'People genuinely happy in their choices seem less often tempted to force them on other people than those who feel martyred and broken by their lives.', 63770, 0), (405479, 'Happiness ... leads none of us by the same route.', 432, 0), (405480, 'Even the lowliest  provided he is whole  can be happy  and in his own . way  perfect.', 62224, 0), (405481, 'Happiness  to some  is elation  to others it is mere stagnation.', 8660, 0), (405482, 'No sooner is it a little calmer with me than it is almost too calm  as though I have the true feeling of myself only when I am unbearably unhappy', 629, 0), (405483, 'Your readiest desire is your path to joy ... even if it destroys you.', 13875, 0), (405484, 'All men have happiness as their object: there are no exceptions. However different the means they employ  they aim at the same end.', 144, 0), (405485, 'We all live with the objective of being happy  our lives are all different and yet the same.', 986, 0), (405486, 'The world is so full of a number of things  I''m sure we should all be as happy as kings.', 449, 0), (405487, 'There is no cosmetic for beauty like happiness.', 63235, 0), (405488, 'Love is a great beautifier.', 296, 0), (405489, 'Taking joy in life is a woman''s best cosmetic.', 63501, 0), (405490, 'Beauty is a radiance that originates from within and comes from inner security and strong character.', 64133, 0), (405491, 'Real happiness is cheap enough  yet how dearly we pay for its counterfeit.', 32228, 0), (405492, 'False happiness renders men stern and proud  and that happiness is never communicated. True happiness renders kind and sensible  and that happiness is always shared.', 48659, 0), (405493, 'Don''t mistake pleasures for happiness. They are a different breed of dog.', 3355, 0), (405494, 'Mirth is better than fun  and happiness is better than mirth.', 221, 0), (405495, 'Amusement is the happiness of those who cannot think.', 3348, 0), (405496, 'Happiness is a small and unworthy goal for something as big and fancy as a whole lifetime  and should be taken in small doses.', 9597, 0), (405497, 'False happiness is like false money  it passes for a long time as well as the true  and serves some ordinary occasions  but when it is brought to the touch  we find the lightness and alloy  and feel the loss.', 3348, 0), (405498, 'There is more to life than just existing and having a pleasant time.', 62240, 0), (405499, 'The test of enjoyment is the remembrance which it leaves behind.', 1014, 0), (405500, 'When I have been unhappy  I have heard an opera ... and it seemed the shrieking of winds  when I am happy  a sparrow''s chirp is delicious to me. But it is not the chirp that makes me happy  but I that make it sweet.', 485, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (405501, 'Happiness depends upon ourselves.', 1116, 0), (405502, 'The U.S. Constitution doesn''t guarantee happiness  only the pursuit of it. Your have to catch up with it yourself.', 1077, 0), (405503, 'Happiness belongs to those who are sufficient unto themselves. For all external sources of happiness and pleasure are  by their very nature  highly uncertain  precarious  ephemeral and subject to chance.', 1304, 0), (405504, 'Most folks are about as happy as they make up their minds to be.', 1012, 0), (405505, 'One is happy as a result of one''s own efforts-once one knows the necessary ingredients of happiness-simple tastes  a certain degree of courage  self-denial to a point  love of work  and  above all  a clear conscience.', 810, 0), (405506, 'Nothing can bring you peace but yourself.', 760, 0), (405507, 'Discontent is want of self-reliance  it is infirmity of will.', 760, 0), (405508, 'I''m happier. ... I guess I made up my mind to be that way.', 64134, 0), (405509, 'The essence of philosophy is that a man should so live that his happiness shall depend as little as possible on external things.', 1328, 0), (405510, 'No one gives joy or sorrow. ... We gather the consequences of our own deeds.', 64135, 0), (405511, 'Happiness  happiness ... the flavor is with you-with you alone  and you can make it as intoxicating as you please.', 1241, 0), (405512, 'Few are they who have never had the chance to achieve happiness ... and fewer those who have taken that chance.', 10019, 0), (405513, 'To win one''s joy through struggle is better than to yield to melancholy.', 8, 0), (405514, 'Life is a romantic business  but you have to make the romance.', 24754, 0), (405515, 'To be obliged to beg our daily happiness from others bespeaks a more lamentable poverty than that of him who begs his daily bread.', 432, 0), (405516, 'Some pursue happiness  others create it.', 33, 0), (405517, 'Man is the artificer of his own happiness.', 1049, 0), (405518, 'The man who makes everything that leads to happiness depend upon himself  and not upon other men  has adopted the very best plan for living happily.', 51, 0), (405519, 'It is not the level of prosperity that makes for happiness but the kinship of heart to heart and the way we look at the world. Both attitudes are within our power  so that a man is happy so long as he chooses to be happy  and no one can stop him.', 2564, 0), (405520, 'Happy is he that chastens himself.', 33, 0), (405521, 'How unhappy is he who cannot forgive himself.', 2904, 0), (405522, 'There is always something left to love. And if you ain''t learned that  you ain''t learned nothing.', 64136, 0), (405523, 'Like swimming  riding  writing or playing golf  happiness can be learned.', 64137, 0), (405524, 'Being happy is something you have to learn. I often surprise myself by saying  "Wow  this is it. I guess I''m happy. I''ve got a home that I love. A career that I love. I''m even feeling more and more at peace with myself." If there''s something else to happiness  let me know. I''m ambitious for that  too.', 12392, 0), (405525, 'Learn how to feel joy.', 1379, 0), (405526, 'Someone once asked me what I regarded as the three most important requirements for happiness. My answer was: "A feeling that you have been honest with yourself and those around you  a feeling that you have done the best you could both in your personal life and in your work  and the ability to love others."', 141, 0), (405527, 'Nine requisites for contented living: Health enough to make work a pleasure. Wealth enough to support your needs. Strength to battle with difficulties and overcome them. Grace enough to confess your sins and forsake them. Patience enough to toil until some good is accomplished. Charity enough to see some good in your neighbor. Love enough to move you to be useful and helpful to others. Faith enough to make real the things of God. Hope enough to remove all anxious fears concerning the future.', 62224, 0), (405528, 'Happiness comes of the capacity to feel deeply  to enjoy simply  to think freely  to risk life  to be needed.', 20188, 0), (405529, 'Do not worry  eat three square meals a day  say your prayers  be courteous to your creditors  keep your digestion good  exercise  go slow and easy. Maybe there are other things your special case requires to make you happy  but  my friend  these I reckon will give you a good lift.', 1012, 0), (405530, 'To love deeply in one direction makes us more loving in all others.', 62617, 0), (405531, 'Have a variety of interests. ... These interests relax the mind and lessen tension on the nervous system. People with many interests live  not only longest  but happiest.', 6065, 0), (405532, 'Build a little fence of trust Around today  Fill the space with loving work  And therein stay.', 64138, 0), (405533, 'This is wisdom: to love wine  beauty  and the heavenly spring. That''s sufficient-the rest is worthless.', 64139, 0), (405534, 'If a man has important work  and enough leisure and income to enable him to do it properly  he is in possession of as much happiness as is good for any of the children of Adam.', 17007, 0), (405535, 'The secret of happiness ... is to be in harmony with existence  to be always calm  always lucid  always willing "to be joined to the universe without being more conscious of it than an idiot " to let each wave of life wash us a little farther up the shore.', 9518, 0), (405536, 'Good friends  good books and a sleepy conscience: this is the ideal life.', 286, 0), (405537, 'The grand essentials to happiness in this life are something to do  something to love and something to hope for.', 2868, 0), (405538, 'The best philosophy is to do one''s duties  to take the world as it comes  submit respectfully to one''s lot  and bless the goodness that has given us so much happiness with it  whatever it is.', 1081, 0), (405539, 'One is happy as a result of one''s own efforts-once one knows the necessary ingredients of happiness-simple tastes  a certain degree of courage  self-denial to a point  love of work  and  above all  a clear conscience.', 810, 0), (405540, 'In order to be utterly happy the only thing necessary is to refrain from comparing this moment with other moments in the past  which I often did not fully enjoy because I was comparing them with other moments of the future.', 8, 0), (405541, 'From birth to age eighteen  a girl needs good parents. From eighteen to thirty-five  she needs good looks. From thirty-five to fifty-five  she needs a good personality. From fifty-five on  she needs good cash.', 62647, 0), (405542, 'To make a man happy  fill his hands with work  his heart with affection  his mind with purpose  his memory with useful knowledge  his future with hope  and his stomach with food.', 64140, 0), (405543, 'For me  happiness came from prayer to a kindly God  faith in a kindly God  love for my fellow man  and doing the very best I could every day of my life. I had looked for happiness in fast living  but it was not there. I tried to find it in money  but it was not there  either. But when I placed myself in tune with what I believe to be fundamental truths of life  when I began to develop my limited ability  to rid my mind of all kinds of tangled thoughts and fill it with zeal and courage and love  when I gave myself a chance by treating myself decently and sensibly  I began to feel the stimulating  warm glow of happiness.', 4028, 0), (405544, 'There are three ingredients in the good life: learning  earning and yearning.', 8661, 0), (405545, 'Work and love-these are the basics. Without them there is neurosis.', 29103, 0), (405546, 'If thou workest at that which is before thee ... expecting nothing  fearing nothing  but satisfied with thy present activity according to Nature  and with heroic truth in every word and sound which thou utterest  thou wilt live happy. And there is no man who is able to prevent this.', 267, 0), (405547, 'Our greatest happiness does not depend on the condition of life in which chance has placed us  but is always the result of a good conscience  good health  occupation and freedom in all just pursuits.', 1207, 0), (405548, 'I believe the recipe for happiness to be just enough money to pay the monthly bills you acquire  a little surplus to give you confidence  a little too much work each day  enthusiasm for your work  a substantial share of good health  a couple of real friends and a wife and children to share life''s beauty with you.', 63471, 0), (405549, 'If we could learn how to balance rest against effort  calmness against strain  quiet against turmoil  we would assure ourselves of joy in living and psychological health for life.', 64141, 0), (405550, 'Five great enemies to peace inhabit us: avarice  ambition  envy  anger and pride. If those enemies were to be banished  we should infallibly enjoy perpetual peace.', 760, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (405551, 'True happiness... arises  in the first place  from the enjoyment of one''s self  and in the next  from the friendship and conversation of a few select companions.', 2868, 0), (405552, 'May you have warmth in your igloo  oil in your lamp  and peace in your heart.', 64142, 0), (405553, 'What can be added to the happiness of man who is in health  out of debt  and has a clear conscience?', 2485, 0), (405554, 'To do the useful thing  to say the courageous thing  to contemplate the beautiful thing: that is enough for one man''s life.', 1067, 0), (405555, 'Let your boat of life be light  packed only with what you need-a homely home and simple pleasures  one or two friends worth the name  someone to love and to love you  a cat  a dog  enough to eat and enough to wear  and a little more than enough to drink  for thirst is a dangerous thing.', 2174, 0), (405556, 'To be glad of life  because it gives you the chance to love and to work and to play and to look up at the stars  to be satisfied with your possessions  but not contented with yourself until you have made the best of them  to despise nothing in the world except falsehood and meanness  and to fear nothing except cowardice  to be governed by your admirations rather than by your disgusts  to covet nothing that is your neighbor''s except his kindness of heart and gentleness of manners  to think seldom of your enemies  often of your friends  and every day of Christ  and to spend as much time as you can  with body and with spirit  in God''s out-of-doors- these are little guideposts on the footpath to peace.', 672, 0), (405557, 'Order your soul  reduce your wants  live in charity  associate in Christian community  obey the laws  trust in Providence.', 63060, 0), (405558, 'Simplicity  clarity  singleness: these are the attributes that give our lives power and vividness and joy.', 64143, 0), (405559, 'To live content with small means  to seek elegance rather than luxury  and refinement rather than fashion  to be worthy  not respectable  and wealthy  not rich  to study hard  think quietly  talk gently  act frankly  to listen to the stars and birds  to babes and sages  with open heart  to bear on cheerfully  do all bravely  awaiting occasions  worry never  in a word to  like the spiritual  unbidden and unconscious  grow up through the common.', 3573, 0), (405560, 'The attributes of a great lady may still be found in the rule of the four S''s: Sincerity  Simplicity  Sympathy  and Serenity.', 31062, 0), (405561, 'Manifest plainness  Embrace simplicity  Reduce selfishness  Have few desires.', 15, 0), (405562, 'Happiness comes of the capacity to feel deeply  to enjoy simply  to think freely  to risk life  to be needed.', 20188, 0), (405563, 'Fear less  hope more  eat less  chew more  whine less  breathe more  talk less  say more  love more  and all good things will be yours.', 1477, 0), (405564, 'Practice easing your way along. Don''t get het up or in a dither. Do your best  take it as it comes. You can handle anything if you think you can. Just keep your cool and your sense of humor.', 54020, 0), (405565, 'To live and let live  without clamor for distinction or recognition  to wait on divine Love  to write truth first on the tablet of one''s own heart-this is the sanity and perfection of living  and my human ideal.', 5264, 0), (405566, 'Do all the good you can  By all the means you can  In all the ways you can  In all the places you can  At all the times you can.', 33, 0), (405567, 'Go placidly amid the noise and the haste  and remember what peace there may be in silence. As far as possible without surrender  be on good terms with all persons. Speak your truth quietly and clearly  and listen to others  even the dull and ignorant  they too have their story. . . . Be yourself. Especially do not feign affection. Neither be cynical about love  for in the face of all aridity and disenchantment it is as perennial as the grass. Take kindly the counsel of the years  gracefully surrendering the things of youth. Nurture strength of spirit to shield you in sudden misfortune. But do not distress yourself with imaginings. Many fears are born of fatigue and loneliness. Beyond a wholesome discipline  be gentle with yourself. You are a child of the universe no less than the trees and the stars  you have a right to be here. And whether or not it is clear to you  no doubt the universe is unfolding as it should. Therefore be at peace with God  whatever you conceive Him to be  and whatever your labours and aspirations  in the noisy confusion of life keep peace with your soul. With all its sham  drudgery and broken dreams  it is still a beautiful world.', 1203, 0), (405568, 'Accept the pain  cherish the joys  resolve the regrets  then can come the best of benedictions-"If I had my life to live over  I''d do it all the same."', 64144, 0), (405569, 'The way of a superior man is threefold: Virtuous  he is free from anxieties  wise  he is free from perplexities  bold  he is free from fear.', 819, 0), (405570, 'The first rule is to keep an untroubled spirit. The second is to look things in the face and know them for what they are.', 267, 0), (405571, 'It is not easy to find happiness in ourselves  and it is not possible to find it elsewhere.', 24996, 0), (405572, 'Joy is the feeling of grinning on the inside.', 64145, 0), (405573, 'It is those who have a deep and real inner life who are best able to deal with the irritating details of outer life.', 9142, 0), (405574, 'To live happily is an inward power of the soul.', 267, 0), (405575, 'The secret of staying young is to live honestly  eat slowly  and lie about your age.', 1814, 0), (405576, 'Virtue  like a dowerless beauty  has more admirers than followers.', 63235, 0), (405577, 'We can build upon foundations anywhere  if they are well and truly laid.', 27841, 0), (405578, 'Though language forms the preacher  ''Tis "good works" make the man.', 23259, 0), (405579, 'All times are beautiful for those who maintain joy within them  but there is no happy or favorable time for those with disconsolate or orphaned souls.', 64146, 0), (405580, 'When you''re in your nineties and looking back  it''s not going to be how much money you made or how many awards you''ve won. It''s really what did you stand for. Did you make a positive difference for people?', 64147, 0), (405581, 'For attractive lips  speak words of kindness. For lovely eyes  seek out the good in people. For a slim figure  share your food with the hungry. For beautiful hair  let a child run his or her fingers through it once a day. For poise  walk with the knowledge you''ll never walk alone.', 999, 0), (405582, 'What you become is what counts.', 16440, 0), (405583, 'If an Arab in the desert were suddenly to discover a spring in his tent  and so would always be able to have water in abundance  how fortunate he would consider himself  so too  when a man who ... is always turned toward the outside  thinking that his happiness lies outside him  finally turns inward and discovers that the source is within him.', 64148, 0), (405584, 'Happiness is not in our circumstances  but in ourselves. It is not something we see  like a rainbow  or feel  like the heat of a fire. Happiness is something we are.', 64149, 0), (405585, 'Seek not outside yourself  heaven is within.', 64150, 0), (405586, 'If we have not peace within ourselves  it is in vain to seek it from outward sources.', 154, 0), (405587, 'Most true happiness comes from one''s inner life  from the disposition of the mind and soul. Admittedly  a good inner life is difficult to achieve  especially in these trying times. It takes reflection and contemplation and self-discipline.', 64151, 0), (405588, 'It''s what you do that makes your soul  not the other way around.', 679, 0), (405589, 'The happiest people seem to be those who have no particular cause for being happy except that they are so.', 4228, 0), (405590, 'I think the inner person is the most important. ... I would like to see an invention that keeps the mind alert. That''s what is important.', 1537, 0), (405591, 'I don''t think that... one gets a flash of happiness once  and never again  it is there within you  and it will come as certainly as death.', 19178, 0), (405592, 'There is no other solution to man''s progress but the day''s honest work  the day''s honest decisions  the day''s generous utterances  and the day''s good deed.', 21495, 0), (405593, 'You have much more power when you are working for the right thing than when you are working for the wrong thing.', 47088, 0), (405594, 'I am convinced that we must train not only the head  but the heart and hand as well.', 64152, 0), (405595, 'Live virtuously  and you cannot die too soon  or live too long.', 64153, 0), (405596, 'A happy life is one which is in accordance with its own nature.', 62237, 0), (405597, 'People see God every day  they just don''t recognize Him.', 27040, 0), (405598, 'We hear voices in solitude  we never hear in the hurry and turmoil of life  we receive counsels and comforts we get under no other condition.', 62313, 0), (405599, 'Happiness is not a possession to be prized  it is a quality of thought  a state of mind.', 1214, 0), (405600, 'Happiness is a butterfly which  when pursued  is always beyond our grasp  but  if you will sit down quietly  may alight upon you.', 650, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (405601, 'Happiness is something that comes into our lives through doors we don''t even remember leaving open.', 2996, 0), (405602, 'To seek after beauty as an end  is a wild goose chase  a will-o''-the-wisp  because it is to misunderstand the very nature of beauty  which is the normal condition of a thing being as it should be.', 64154, 0), (405603, 'Perfect happiness is the absence of striving for happiness.', 62218, 0), (405604, 'This will be triumph! This will be happiness! Yea  that very thing  happiness  which I have been pursuing all my life  and have never yet overtaken.', 63414, 0), (405605, 'I don''t sit around thinking that I''d like to have another husband  only another man would make me think that way.', 12702, 0), (405606, 'Pleasure is very seldom found where it is sought. Our brightest blazes are commonly kindled by unexpected sparks.', 2087, 0), (405607, 'A sure way to lose happiness  I found  is to want it at the expense of everything else.', 13058, 0), (405608, 'Those who seek happiness miss it  and those who discuss it  lack it.', 13875, 0), (405609, 'Inspiration never arrived when you were searching for it.', 20537, 0), (405610, 'Nothing is more hopeless than a scheme of merriment.', 2087, 0), (405611, 'Happiness is never stopping to think if you are.', 64155, 0), (405612, 'It is the paradox of life that the way to miss pleasure is to seek it first. The very first condition of lasting happiness is that a life should be full of purpose  aiming at something outside self.', 64018, 0), (405613, 'If you pursue happiness you''ll never find it.', 3342, 0), (405614, 'Some of us might find happiness if we quit struggling so desperately for it.', 5249, 0), (405615, 'Seek not happiness too greedily  and be not fearful of unhappiness.', 15, 0), (405616, 'The man of pleasure  by a vain attempt to be more happy than any man can be  is often more miserable than most men.', 432, 0), (405617, 'The bird of paradise alights only on the hand that does not grasp.', 2911, 0), (405618, 'The only way to happiness is never to give happiness a thought.', 24179, 0), (405619, 'Everyone chases after happiness  not noticing that happiness is at their heels.', 1140, 0), (405620, 'Seek to do good  and you will find that happiness will run after you.', 17463, 0), (405621, 'Deliberately to pursue happiness is not the surest way of achieving it. Seek it for its own sake and I doubt whether you will find it.', 23094, 0), (405622, 'Enjoyment is not a goal  it is a feeling that accompanies important ongoing activity.', 11646, 0), (405623, 'If only we''d stop trying to be happy we''d have a pretty good time.', 426, 0), (405624, 'Most men pursue pleasure with such breathless haste that they hurry past it.', 3131, 0), (405625, 'Happiness comes most to persons who seek it least  and think least about it. It is not an object to be sought  it is a state to be induced. It must follow and not lead. It must overtake you  and not you overtake it.', 1069, 0), (405626, 'Happiness sneaks in through a door you didn''t know you left open.', 26603, 0), (405627, 'Happiness is like a cat. If you try to coax it or call it  it will avoid you. It will never come. But if you pay no attention to it and go about your business  you''ll find it rubbing against your legs and jumping into your lap.', 64156, 0), (405628, 'One must never look for happiness: one meets it by the way.', 1921, 0), (405629, 'They seemed to come suddenly upon happiness as if they had surprised a butterfly in the winter woods.', 426, 0), (405630, 'Happiness in this world  when it comes  comes incidentally. Make it the object of pursuit  and it leads us on a wild-goose chase  and is never attained. Follow some other object  and very possibly we may find that we have caught happiness without dreaming of it.', 650, 0), (405631, 'Happiness and beauty are by-products. Folly is the direct pursuit of happiness and beauty.', 266, 0), (405632, 'It is the very pursuit of happiness that thwarts happiness.', 63222, 0), (405633, 'If you ever find happiness by hunting for it  you will find it  as the old woman did her lost spectacles  safe on her nose all the time.', 3355, 0), (405634, 'Happiness is not a goal  it is a byproduct.', 141, 0), (405635, 'Happiness is mostly a by-product of doing what makes us feel fulfilled.', 64157, 0), (405636, 'Happiness is something you get as a by-product in the process of making something else.', 1032, 0), (405637, 'Happiness is not a horse  you cannot harness it.', 7652, 0), (405638, 'The attainment of justice is the highest human endeavor.', 64158, 0), (405639, 'Conscience  as I understand it  is the impulse to do the right thing because it is right  regardless of personal ends  and has nothing whatever to do with the ability to distinguish between right and wrong.', 62850, 0), (405640, 'I cannot and will not cut my conscience to fit this year''s fashions.', 1991, 0), (405641, 'The principles we live by  in business and in social life  are the most important part of happiness.', 41475, 0), (405642, 'If you aren''t good at loving yourself  you will have a difficult time loving anyone  since you''ll resent the time and energy you give another person that you aren''t even giving to yourself.', 28913, 0), (405643, 'Happiness is when what you think  what you say  and what you do are in harmony.', 32, 0), (405644, 'A good message will always find a messenger.', 62313, 0), (405645, 'It''s no good saying one thing and doing another.', 22129, 0), (405646, 'There can be no happiness if the things we believe in are different from the things we do.', 21457, 0), (405647, 'Let how you live your life stand for something  no matter how small and incidental it may seem.', 63992, 0), (405648, 'Happy is the man who ventures boldly to defend what he holds dear.', 782, 0), (405649, 'It is necessary to the happiness of man that he be mentally faithful to himself.', 1131, 0), (405650, 'Happiness is that state of consciousness which proceeds from the achievement of one''s values.', 631, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (405651, 'It is the chiefest point of happiness that a man is willing to be what he is.', 1966, 0), (405652, 'Resolve to be thyself  and know that who finds himself  loses his misery.', 460, 0), (405653, 'There is only one history of any importance  and it is the history of what you once believed in  and the history of what you came to believe in.', 64159, 0), (405654, 'The needle of our conscience is as good a compass as any.', 64160, 0), (405655, 'But what is happiness except the simple harmony between a man and the life he leads?', 532, 0), (405656, 'That kind of life is most happy which affords us most opportunities of gaining our own esteem.', 2087, 0), (405657, 'Happiness is not something you get  but something you do.', 63122, 0), (405658, 'Happiness is action.', 36117, 0), (405659, 'I am enjoying to a full that period of reflection which is the happiest conclusion to a life of action.', 307, 0), (405660, 'Action may not always bring happiness  but there is no happiness without action.', 1782, 0), (405661, 'I want a busy life  a just mind  and a timely death.', 751, 0), (405662, 'Happiness is often the result of being too busy to be miserable.', 33, 0), (405663, 'Painting''s not important. The important thing is keeping busy.', 1614, 0), (405664, 'To attain happiness in another world we need only to believe something  to secure it in this world  we must do something.', 63146, 0), (405665, 'To fill the hour  and leave no crevice ... that is happiness.', 760, 0), (405666, 'If you observe a really happy man  you will find ... that he is happy in the course of living life twenty-four crowded hours of each day.', 64161, 0), (405667, 'I find my joy of living in the fierce and ruthless battles of life.', 8978, 0), (405668, 'Happiness is an expression of the soul in considered actions.', 1116, 0), (405669, 'We must be doing something to be happy.', 8948, 0), (405670, 'Happiness lies in the fulfillment of the spirit through the body.', 9518, 0), (405671, 'We must not seek happiness in peace  but in conflict.', 64162, 0), (405672, 'Happiness walks on busy feet.', 64163, 0), (405673, 'Our actions are the springs of our happiness or misery.', 64164, 0), (405674, 'The formula for complete happiness is to be very busy.', 6168, 0), (405675, 'The busiest man is the happiest man.', 64165, 0), (405676, 'To be busy is man''s only happiness.', 286, 0), (405677, 'The only way to avoid being miserable is not to have enough leisure to wonder whether you are happy or not.', 266, 0), (405678, 'The happiest people are those who are too busy to notice whether they are or not.', 5249, 0), (405679, 'In great moments life seems neither right nor wrong  but something greater: it seems inevitable.', 64098, 0), (405680, 'Happiness ... can exist only in acceptance.', 6986, 0), (405681, 'Knowledge of what is possible is the beginning of happiness.', 2683, 0), (405682, 'There is only one way to happiness  and that is to cease worrying about things which are beyond the power of our will.', 1328, 0), (405683, 'Happiness comes from ... some curious adjustment to life.', 4819, 0), (405684, 'Happy is he who learns to bear what he cannot change!', 62240, 0), (405685, 'The secret of happiness is not in doing what one likes  but in liking what one has to do.', 63085, 0), (405686, 'He is happy whose circumstances suit his temper  but he is more excellent who suits his temper to any circumstances.', 2498, 0), (405687, 'Happiness is experienced when your life gives you what you are willing to accept.', 62252, 0), (405688, 'Peace of mind is that mental condition in which you have accepted the worst.', 1317, 0), (405689, 'Life is not always what one wants it to be  but to make the best of it as it is  is the only way of being happy.', 62234, 0), (405690, 'We deem those happy who from the experience of life have learned to bear its ills  without being overcome by them.', 21406, 0), (405691, 'This is true joy of life-being used for a purpose that is recognized by yourself as a mighty one ... instead of being a feverish  selfish little clod of ailments and grievances  complaining that the world will not devote itself to making you happy.', 266, 0), (405692, 'Never mind your happiness  do your duty.', 1167, 0), (405693, 'Human happiness and moral duty are inseparably connected.', 3161, 0), (405694, 'When we ... devote ourselves to the strict and unsparing performance of duty  then happiness comes of itself.', 3896, 0), (405695, 'Seek happiness for its own sake  and you will not find it  seek for duty  and happiness will follow as the shadow comes with the sunshine.', 45999, 0), (405696, 'True happiness ... is not attained through self-gratification  but through fidelity to a worthy purpose.', 701, 0), (405697, 'The only true happiness comes from squandering ourselves for a purpose.', 8676, 0), (405698, 'Happiness is the natural flower of duty.', 22130, 0), (405699, 'The happiest excitement in life is to be convinced that one is fighting for all one is worth on behalf of some clearly seen and deeply felt good.', 9314, 0), (405700, 'True happiness  we are told  consists in getting out of one''s self. But the point is not only to get out  you must stay out. And to stay out  you must have some absorbing errand.', 561, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (405701, 'The secret of living is to find ... the pivot of a concept on which you can make your stand.', 23247, 0), (405702, 'A man''s happiness: to do the things proper to man.', 267, 0), (405703, 'Happy [is] the man who knows his duties!', 64020, 0), (405704, 'The only ones among you who will be really happy are those who will have sought and found how to serve.', 1006, 0), (405705, 'He who never sacrificed a present to a future good  or a personal to a general one  can speak of happiness only as the blind speak of color.', 2053, 0), (405706, 'There is no happiness except in the realization that we have accom plished something.', 1796, 0), (405707, 'I believe half the unhappiness in life comes from people being afraid to go straight at things.', 64021, 0), (405708, 'The full-grown modern human being ... is conscious of touching the highest pinnacle of fulfillment... when he is consumed in the service of an idea  in the conquest of the goal pursued.', 63974, 0), (405709, 'Happiness is essentially a state of going somewhere  wholeheartedly  one-directionally  without regret or reservation.', 64019, 0), (405710, 'Happiness is the overcoming of not unknown obstacles toward a known goal.', 4932, 0), (405711, 'Give a man health and a course to steer  and he''ll never stop to trouble about whether he''s happy or not.', 266, 0), (405712, 'Having a goal is a state of happiness.', 63980, 0), (405713, 'Happiness lies in the joy of achieve ment and the thrill of creative effort.', 63327, 0), (405714, 'Without duty  life is soft and bone less.', 8895, 0), (405715, 'It is always the simple that produces the marvelous.', 62313, 0), (405716, 'Happiness consists not in having much  but in being content with little.', 63235, 0), (405717, 'Man is meant for happiness and this happiness is in him  in the satisfaction of the daily needs of his existence.', 93, 0), (405718, 'I have had more than half a century of such happiness. A great deal of worry and sorrow  too  but never a worry or a sorrow that was not offset by a purple iris  a lark  a bluebird  or a dewy morning glory.', 25698, 0), (405719, 'A multitude of small delights constitute happiness.', 1165, 0), (405720, 'The happiness of life is made up of minute fractions-the little  soon-forgotten charities of a kiss or smile  a kind look  a heart-felt compliment  and the countless infinitesimals of pleasurable and genial feeling.', 1910, 0), (405721, 'For me it is sufficient to have a corner by my hearth  a book and a friend  and a nap undisturbed by creditors or grief.', 64166, 0), (405722, 'A happy life is made up of little things ... a gift sent  a letter written  a call made  a recommendation given  transportation provided  a cake made  a book lent  a check sent.', 64167, 0), (405723, 'Yes  there is a Nirvanah  it is in leading your sheep to a green pasture  and in putting your child to sleep  and in writing the last line of your poem.', 81, 0), (405724, 'First health  then wealth  then pleasure  and do not owe anything to anybody.', 33381, 0), (405725, 'I know well that happiness is in little things.', 485, 0), (405726, 'Sooner or later we all discover that the important moments in life are not the advertised ones  not the birthdays  the graduations  the weddings  not the great goals achieved. The real milestones are less prepossessing. They come to the door of memory.', 2137, 0), (405727, 'There is nothing like staying at home for real comfort.', 24, 0), (405728, 'I don''t think about whether people will remember me or not. I''ve been an okay person. I''ve learned a lot. I''ve taught people a thing or two. That''s what''s important.', 1537, 0), (405729, 'What would life be without art? Science prolongs life. To consist of what-eating  drinking  and sleeping? What is the good of living longer if it is only a matter of satisfying the requirements that sustain life? All this is nothing without the charm of art.', 64168, 0), (405730, 'It is by studying little things that we attain the great knowledge of having as little misery and as much happiness as possible.', 2087, 0), (405731, 'The happiest people I have known in this world have been the Saints-and  after these  the men and women who get immediate and conscious enjoyment from little things.', 4819, 0), (405732, 'The little things are infinitely the most important.', 64169, 0), (405733, 'We women ought to put first things first. Why should we mind if men have their faces on the money  as long as we get our hands on it?', 51389, 0), (405734, 'Eating is not merely a material pleasure. Eating well gives a spectacular joy to life and contributes immensely to goodwill and happy companionship. It is of great importance to the morale.', 64170, 0), (405735, 'I am beginning to learn that it is the sweet  simple things of life which are the real ones after all.', 17296, 0), (405736, 'Happiness consists more in small conveniences or pleasures that occur every day  than in great pieces of good fortune that happen but seldom.', 1077, 0), (405737, 'The happiness of most people is not ruined by great catastrophes or fatal errors  but by the repetition of slowly destructive little things.', 63926, 0), (405738, 'Enjoy the little things  for one day you may look back and realize they were the big things.', 1321, 0), (405739, 'Why not learn to enjoy the little things-there are so many of them.', 33, 0), (405740, 'Anyone who''s a great kisser I''m always interested in.', 863, 0), (405741, 'Moderation. Small helpings. Sample a little bit of everything. These are the secrets of happiness and good health.', 1537, 0), (405742, 'The best things are nearest: breath in your nostrils  light in your eyes  flowers at your feet  duties at your hand  the path of God just before you. Then do not grasp at the stars  but do life''s plain  common work as it comes  certain that daily duties and daily bread are the sweetest things of life.', 449, 0), (405743, 'In violent and chaotic times such as these  our only chance for survival lies in creating our own little islands of sanity and order  in making little havens of our homes.', 64171, 0), (405744, 'Small kindnesses  small courtesies  small considerations  habitually practiced in our social intercourse  give a greater charm to the character than the display of great talents and accomplishments.', 64172, 0), (405745, 'For most of life  nothing wonderful happens. If you don''t enjoy getting up and working and finishing your work and sitting down to a meal with family or friends  then the chances are you''re not going to be very happy. If someone bases his happiness or unhappiness on major events like a great new job  huge amounts of money  a flawlessly happy marriage or a trip to Paris  that person isn''t going to be happy much of the time. If  on the other hand  happiness depends on a good breakfast  flowers in the yard  a drink or a nap  then we are more likely to live with quite a bit of happiness.', 1350, 0), (405746, 'The mere sense of living is joy enough.', 91, 0), (405747, 'The true way to soften one''s troubles is to solace those of others.', 64173, 0), (405748, 'To complain that life has no joys while there is a single creature whom we can relieve by our bounty  assist by our counsels or enliven by our presence  is... just as rational as to die of thirst with the cup in our hands.', 63812, 0), (405749, 'We learn the inner secret of happiness when we learn to direct our inner drives  our interest  and our attention to something besides ourselves.', 64174, 0), (405750, 'Little deeds of kindness  little words of love  Help to make earth happy like the heaven up above.', 64175, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (405751, 'In about the same degree as you are helpful  you will be happy.', 64176, 0), (405752, 'Hire the best. Pay them fairly. Communicate frequently. Provide challenges and rewards. Believe in them. Get out of their way and they''ll knock your socks off.', 64177, 0), (405753, 'Treat a horse like a woman and a woman like a horse. And they''ll both win for you.', 64178, 0), (405754, 'Invest in the human soul. Who knows  it might be a diamond in the rough.', 25698, 0), (405755, 'All the goodness  beauty  and perfection of a human being belong to the one who knows how to recognize these qualities.', 63159, 0), (405756, 'You cannot always have happiness  but you can always give happiness.', 33, 0), (405757, 'The nice thing about teamwork is that you always have others on your side.', 64179, 0), (405758, 'No one can sincerely try to help another without helping himself.', 48445, 0), (405759, 'Happiness is a by-product of helping others.', 64180, 0), (405760, 'The most exquisite pleasure is giving pleasure to others.', 5879, 0), (405761, 'No man can live happily who regards himself alone  who turns everything to his own advantage. Thou must live for another if thou wishest to live for thyself.', 62237, 0), (405762, 'Scatter seeds of kindness everywhere you go  Scatter bits of courtesy-watch them grow and grow. Gather buds of friendship  keep them till full-blown  You will find more happiness than you have ever known.', 64181, 0), (405763, 'If all our happiness is bound up entirely in our personal circumstances  it is difficult not to demand of life more than it has to give.', 95, 0), (405764, 'No man is more cheated than the selfish man.', 2175, 0), (405765, 'The habit of being uniformly considerate toward others will bring increased happiness to you.', 31710, 0), (405766, 'If you have not often felt the joy of doing a kind act  you have neglected much  and most of all yourself.', 64182, 0), (405767, 'We cannot hold a torch to light another''s path without brightening our own.', 11160, 0), (405768, 'Life becomes harder for us when we live for others  but it also becomes richer and happier.', 1006, 0), (405769, 'Happiness ... consists in giving  and in serving others.', 45086, 0), (405770, 'Pleasure is a reciprocal  no one feels it who does not at the same time give it. To be pleased  one must please.', 62413, 0), (405771, 'He that despiseth his neighbor sin-neth  but he that hath mercy on the poor  happy is he.', 5587, 0), (405772, 'Instinct teaches us to look for happiness outside ourselves.', 144, 0), (405773, 'A bit of fragrance always clings to the hand that gives you roses.', 7652, 0), (405774, 'When you dig another out of their troubles  you find a place to bury your own.', 33, 0), (405775, 'One thing I know: the only ones among you who will be really happy are those who will have sought and found how to serve.', 1006, 0), (405776, 'Caring about others  running the risk of feeling  and leaving an impact on people  brings happiness.', 63282, 0), (405777, 'The entire sum of existence is the magic of being needed by just one person.', 64183, 0), (405778, 'One of the things I keep learning is that the secret of being happy is doing things for other people.', 39403, 0), (405779, 'Make one person happy each day and in forty years you will have made 14 600 human beings happy for a little time  at least.', 64184, 0), (405780, 'The most satisfying thing in life is to have been able to give a large part of oneself to others.', 531, 0), (405781, 'To be kind to all  to like many and love a few  to be needed and wanted by those we love  is certainly the nearest we can come to happiness.', 16076, 0), (405782, 'Seldom can the heart be lonely  If it seeks a lonelier still  Self-forgetting  seeking only Emptier cups of love to fill.', 63325, 0), (405783, 'The older you get  the more you realize that kindness is synonymous with happiness.', 4826, 0), (405784, 'There is no happiness in 